<br />

<h2 class="pen"><a rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=929" title="Permanent link to this article">vacation musings</a></h2>

<div class="post">

<div class="entrytext">

	<p>It was nice to play tourist for once. We took a trip to Louisville on business actually and went around after we dropped off some pottery for jurying.</p>

	<p>Highlights I&#8217;d recommend: Gallopaloosa&#8217;s artistic horse sculptures is a lot of fun. Lexington, Ky., did horses a few years ago, but Louisville&#8217;s are on the whole better.</p>

	<p>Great exhibit at the Kentucky Museum of Art and Design. Two galleries full of pottery. Our favorite was &#8220;Splendid Table&#8221; pots for food. Lots of pots we&#8217;d love to own. &#8220;Tea for Two&#8221; is of tea sets, but it failed to fulfill the promise of tea sets that would be used in intimate settings between two spouses, friends or lovers. The work just didn&#8217;t capture the theme.</p>

	<p>Wild Oats is a fun natural food store on Shelbyville Road. We finally got to GlassWorks, but it was too late for the tour. At least they didn&#8217;t charge us to watch the hot glass demonstrations.</p>

	<p>Louisville&#8217;s art scene is hopping. For a gallery guide check out <a href="http://www.looklouisvilleart.com">LOOK</a></p>

	<p>I&#8217;ll add links later. Notes on Cincinnati coming as well.</p>



 

<p class="postmetadata alt">

<small>This entry was posted on Jul  8 by <a href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a>. You can skip to the end and leave a response using the comment form.</small></p>

</div>

</div>




	

